snippet.textDisplay: Not the Austrian military, Australian! Although a military version has existed since the beginning and the Austrian and other European armies had them, this didn't include the 6x6. When the Land Rover Defender military version was discontinued, which included a 6x6 version, the only similar vehicle left for light transport for the Australian army was the military version of the G-Wagen. The army bought well over a thousand, including a 6x6 version for heavier duty use. I guess they decided to capitalise on the fact it now existed with parts and body panels, so a commercial/private version was created. I live near an army base and you can see them, along with Unimogs which the army also bought, on the road all the time, mostly with learner plates for training army personnel. Interestingly the military 4x4 version can be bought as a Pro model (also called 4x4²), which looks and is outfitted the same as the 6x6 but with 4 wheels, including portal axles, tyre pressure inflation, dual shocks, etc.
